</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-67_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong> Adhering to ethical standards </strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-69_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Journalists should adhere to the NUJ Code of Conduct, which outlines ethical principles such as accuracy, fairness, and accountability. This code is a guideline for maintaining integrity and public trust in journalism.






























</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-71_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Ensuring legal compliance
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-73_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Journalists must know and comply with relevant legislation, such as the Data Protection Act 2018 and the Defamation Act 2013. Understanding these laws is essential for avoiding legal pitfalls and protecting both journalists and their sources.
































</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-75_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Promoting press freedom
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-77_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Organisations should support press freedom by resisting undue influence from political or corporate entities. This includes safeguarding journalists' ability to report freely and without fear of retaliation.

































</p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-dtMgUX gYEGeC pf-79_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Encouraging continuous professional Development
</strong></h3><p class="sc-cZMNgc hqfPHB pf-81_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Continuous learning is crucial in the fast-paced media industry. Employers should encourage their staff to participate in training programmes offered by the NUJ and other professional bodies. This ensures that journalists remain skilled and knowledgeable about the latest industry developments.




































